title: Entrance to Underground Bunkers
description: This is the top end of tunnels leading deep into the ground beneath the Northern Line.   The site is now used for archive storage but was built as a giant air-raid shelter connected to Tottenham Court Road Station.   Similar shelters were built beneath other stations (Look at Clapham Common), the idea being to join them up after the war to create a new deep-level high-speed Northern Line with only limited stops. The idea was abandoned to save costs, as new signalling equipment allows trains to run more frequently.

title: Raymond Revuebar
description: The Raymond Revuebar was a theater and strip club at 11 Walker's Court, in the heart of London's Soho district. For many years, it was the only venue in London that offered full-frontal, on-stage nudity of the sort commonly seen in other cities in Europe and North America.[1] Its huge brightly lit sign declaring it to be the "World Centre of Erotic Entertainment" made the Revuebar a local landmark.

title: Wales Office
description:
The Wales Office (Welsh: Swyddfa Cymru) is a United Kingdom government department. It is a replacement for the old Welsh Office, which had extensive responsibility for governing Wales prior to Welsh devolution in 1999. Its current incarnation is significantly less powerful: it is primarily responsible for carrying out the few functions remaining with the Secretary of State for Wales that have not been transferred already to National Assembly for Wales; and for securing funds for Wales as part of the annual budgetary settlement.

Official website: http://www.walesoffice.gov.uk/

title: Central London Samaritans
description:
Samaritans offer confidential support to anyone passing through a crisis or thinking of taking their own lives. They offer time and space for people to express their feelings, helping them to talk through their options and find a way to face the future. They are not a religious or political organisation. They don't judge and don't offer advice.

Central London Samaritans is the largest branch in the UK with purpose built premises located in the heart of Soho where Samaritan volunteers talk to callers 365 days a year on the phone, by email or face to face.

Visiting times are between the hours of 9am and 9pm. Alternatively, you can telephone or email anytime, 24 hours a day, throughout the year.

title: Charing Cross Library
description:
Charing Cross Library is situated in the heart of theatreland in London's West End.
It is a busy library serving residents, commuters and the local Chinese community; the building also houses the Chinese Library.

There is a music collection with a wide range of CDs, there are frequent Employment Advice sessions, and regular sessions for the Under 5s are held in the library.
You can get up-to-date information about any events taking place in the library by visiting the News section.

title: Brydges Place - London's narrowest alley
description:
Connecting St Martin's Lane with Bedfordbury, this is an extremely narrow street, only wide enough for one person along most of its length.  Despite this several pubs and businesses do have entrances opening onto the street.  It's so thin that the street lights are connected to both sides of the road.

Note that the 'wide section' drawn in the centre does not actually exist (Wikimapia does not permit polygons as long and narrow as this street!).

http://www.urban75.org/london/brydges-place.html
